^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The play was ok, but we can discuss the bidding. When partner responds one of a major to a one of a minor opener it is often right to raise with 3 card support particularly when responder bids spades. Raising partner's major tends to show four, but it only promises three, assuming the hand is appropriate. You should raise a 1S response to 2S with  three card support, if you have three to a top honor, and shortness somewhere. |
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also, Kerrie has an awkward hand point wise. She is too weak to jump shift, she only has three spades, and a jump to 3S shows four card support. If she had another spade instead of say a diamond, then 3S would have been a good bid. But since she only has three card support, she can only bid 2S. However, if Hope has 5 and more than a min, that is encouraging. Basically, you should raise responder's 1 of a major to 2 with three card support, when you have shortness somewhere and three to an honor.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now it turns out Kerrie can also save the auction another way. Once she bids 2D, and Hope bids 2H, Kerrie can bid 2S. That shows exactly 3-5-4-1 distribution and Hope can bid accordingly, passing in this case. But remember, 2D is not forcing so responder, with 5 spades, will often pass 2D when you really want to play in spades which is why 2S is better than 2D initially.|
