^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Very nice Kristy. First of all, why didn't I make a negative double. Because I have such good hearts and a very good hand. So, 3H was clear. Now, what should Kristy do over 3H? She has enough points that we should be in game and I think 4S is warranted. Even opposite a singleton, her suit is good enough. It is very unlucky she got a 5-1 break. In fact, most of the time the suit plays ok over a void. So, since she knows we have game, and spades is likely to be a good suit, 4S is a good bid. |
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One more comment. East should consider bidding 4D right away rather than 3. If willing to bid 4 over 3 of a major, then bid 4 right away. It is much more effective to bid 4D right away than bid 3D followed by 4D. It takes up more room, makes it harder to communicate. So, when you preempt, decide how high you are willing to go, and do it right away. That is the most effective way. Had East bid 4D I probably still bid 4H, and North still bids 4S. However, many hands it will work out well to bid 4D.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As to the play which is very unclear. If spades break 4-2, once East shifts to a club, there are 11 tricks on the hand. Therefore, I like starting to draw trumps. However, once spades don't break it is not clear what to do. I think the best play is to draw 4 rounds, and play a heart and hope West has the heart Ace. West certainly should not have any more diamonds based on the auction. It is important, remember, to take clues from the bidding and since East has AK of diamonds and preempted, probably doesn't have A of hearts. |
